INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1109_L064$$, 2026, $$Training Simulation Support (TSS) - TSS directly contributes to Marine Corps training and readiness requirements by providing comprehensive solutions that align with the future operation concepts outlined in
 Force Design documentation. These services encompass the provisioning of Live, Virtual, and Constructive (LVC) training elements, leveraging both contractor-provided and government-developed/available
 training tools to enhance warfighter proficiency, operational readiness, Marine Corps Lethality, sustainment of force readiness, and strategic deterrence across the Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF) by
 delivering realistic and effective training experiences that reinforce Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs) through focused repetitions and sets. The current execution of investment authority is for the Live,
 Virtual, Constructive Training Environment (LVC-TE) program. LVC-TE provides an enterprise-wide capability as part of the Marine Corps Training Environment. A system of systems architecture, the LVC-TE
 will provide enterprise services to execute a persistent, consistent, and collective training capability. The resulting shared synthetic training environment will provide distributed collective training capability for
 individuals, units and staff to get training using enterprise services and data configured and managed by the program. Funding supports hardware procurements to mitigate obsolescence and incorporate future/
 evolving requirements.

 Range and Training Area Management (RTAM) - The Marine Corps' training resources play a critical role in the Services' ability to implement Force Design to prepare individuals and units to meet the demands
 of current and future operating environments. To meet its Title 10 responsibilities, the Marine Corps requires a portfolio of ranges and training areas (RTAs) and associated training systems to maintain
 an advantage over pacing threats. RTAs support current, evolving, and future validated standards-based training requirements and are configured to support various levels of training from the individual
 to the Marine Air Ground Task Force (MAGTF) level, utilizing the weapons, munitions, platforms, and systems in the Marine Corps inventory. The Marine Corps RTA Management Program provides for a
 comprehensive and integrated program, which supports entry level training, formal schools, the execution of service-level training exercises, and enables the Fleet Marine Forces (FMF) to achieve and sustain
 combat readiness. Two critical functional capability areas of the program are to provide training environments and range management and control. Training environments consist of modern, effective, and
 sustainable range training solutions to include threat representation (ground / air) target systems, battlefield effects, range instrumentation (feedback / scoring) systems, After Action Review (AAR) technologies,
 electromagnetic spectrum denied and degraded training environments, urban training capabilities, and other training resources. In addition, modernization of training systems is essential to preclude deterioration
 of fielded systems and to prevent decreased effectiveness and availability of RTAs for use by the FMF and formal schools. Major system components of modernization include Known Distance Automated
 Scoring (KDAS), Electromagnetic Warfare Ground Instrumented Range (EWGIR), Combat Training Environments (CTE), Tactical Video Capture System (TVCS), interactive targets, Range Training Aids Portfolio
 (RTAP), individual and vehicle tracking systems, aviation tracking systems, and the Live Fire Evaluation Tool (LFET). The integration and coordination amongst multiple organizations across the Force (e.g.,
 Headquarters Marine Corps support establishment, installations, and the FMF) facilitates the prioritization of efforts to make informed and educated decisions that affect RTA resources. Range management and
 control systems enable range operations personnel to observe on-range event activities in real-time, provide directions to/from range personnel, and make the event-related data available to other observers.
 Range control provides the critical service of coordinating and/or de-conflicting training events thereby fostering a safe training environment while maximizing the use of RTAs. The procurement of Integrated$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
