INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1508_L019$$, 2026, $$The 1350 Infantry Weapons Ammunition budget procures and provides the Fleet Marine Force with essential small- and medium-caliber ammunition. This ammunition is critical to maintaining Marine Corps
 readiness, as it enables Marines to train effectively and remain prepared to fight. The budget is comprehensive, with dedicated funding for First Destination Transportation, as needed, to support programmatic
 goals and ensure the timely delivery of munitions, which directly supports readiness objectives.

 The small-caliber ammunition portfolio covers all conventional types: 5.56mm, 7.62mm, 9mm, 6.5mm, 10- and 12-gauge, .22, .30, .38, .40, .45, .300, .338, and .50 caliber rounds. These munitions support many
 service weapons. The 5.56mm cartridge feeds the M16 Rifle, M4 Carbine, and M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW). The 7.62mm cartridge feeds the M240 Machine Gun, M24 Sniper Weapon System, M110
 Semi-automatic Sniper System, and M14 Rifle. Service pistols like the M9, M17, and M18 use the 9mm cartridge. Specialized platforms use the .300 cartridge in the M2010 Enhanced Sniper Rifle and the .50
 cartridge in the M2A1 Machine Gun and M107 Sniper Rifle. This exhibit includes suitable substitutes, like-items, and legacy items.

 The medium-caliber ammunition portfolio includes 20mm, 25mm, 30mm, and 40mm rounds. These munitions deliver high lethality against point and area targets from handheld, crew-served, and ground-platform
 weapons, supporting operational readiness. The group includes armor-piercing, high-explosive, smoke, illumination, training, and anti-personnel cartridges to defeat light armor, materiel, and personnel, keeping
 units prepared for diverse missions.

 The procurement process for this portfolio maximizes efficiency. The Joint Program Executive Office, Armament and Ammunition (JPEO A&A), via the Single Manager for Conventional Ammunition (SMCA),
 which consolidates all service purchases. The Product Manager for Ammunition manages non-SMCA items internally, with support from Naval Surface Warfare Center (NSWC) Corona, Crane, or Dahlgren.
 SMCA or an NSWC provides pricing for each contract.

 A key budget impact is the long procurement lead time for small- and medium-caliber ammunition, which ranges from 12 months to 6 years. These extended timelines can lead to funding gaps and inventory
 shortages if not carefully managed. Ensuring consistent, predictable funding is critical to maintaining supply continuity and preventing gaps that could compromise Marine readiness.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                    Date: April 2026
Appropriation / Budget Activity / Budget Sub Activity:                                                                 P-1 Line Item Number / Title:
