INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1508_L020$$, 2026, $$In support of Force Design and Marine Corps readiness to address Littoral Operations in Contested Environments and the Indo-Pacific, the Family of Combat Support Munitions includes demolition items,
 handheld grenades, vehicle launched grenades, pyrotechnic devices, land mines, and non-lethal items.

 Demolition items provide high explosives for the purpose of destroying or altering man-made, natural objects, and/or obstacles. These explosive charges include blasting caps, impulse cartridges, block charges,
 shaped charges, flexible-linear charges, detonating cord, explosive sheet/cable, canine explosive scent kit items, chain cutters, military dynamite, and 12-Gauge cartridges used for Explosive Ordnance Disposal
 (EOD). Demolition munition charges are used for general demolition, cutting, breaching, cratering, and destruction of abandoned equipment/ammunition.

 Also included in this profile are all handheld offensive/vehicle launched grenades, pyrotechnics/simulator devices, and land mines used by Marine Corps ground forces. This budget also includes colored/
 obscuration/irritant smoke grenades, and various pyrotechnics devices used in training to simulate battlefield effects.

 Additionally, this budget line item also includes non-lethal munition variants such as 12-Gauge cartridges, 40MM cartridges, and the diversionary/non-lethal hand grenades. These munitions are intended to
 incapacitate, warn or drive off targeted personnel and/or materiel while minimizing permanent injury to personnel and damage to property in the target area and/or environment.

 These munitions are procured either via Joint Program Executive Office, Armament and Ammunition (JPEO A&A)/Single Manager for Conventional Ammunition (SMCA) or Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane,
 IN (NSWC Crane) and NSWC Dahlgren, VA, using contracts that consolidate all Services buys into their procurement contract actions.

 These munitions have a procurement lead-time of 12-36 months before delivery.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
