INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1611_L024$$, 2027, $$Medium Landing Ship (LSM) is a medium-sized landing ship that enables distributed maneuver and logistics such as Distributed Maritime Operations (DMO), Littoral Operations in a Contested Environment
 (LOCE), and Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations (EABO), in support of the Marine Littoral Regiment (MLR). It is designed to fill the gap in capability between the Navy's large, multipurpose amphibious
 warfare class ships and smaller landing vessels. This ship will deploy tailored logistics, select power projection and support strike capabilities via the embarked MLR.

 The FY26 NDAA introduced a new acquisition requirement, mandating the use of a Vessel Construction Manager (VCM) for the LSM program. To leverage the VCM authorization and accelerate delivery, the
 Navy will designate the LSM program as a Middle Tier of Acquisition - Rapid Fielding (MTA-RF) effort. This approach will more quickly field the LSM, a vessel designed to transport and land naval expeditionary
 forces and their equipment in contested environments to support the Marine Corps' Force Design in the Indo-Pacific. One ship is directed to Bollinger, and four directed to Fincantieri Marinette Marine, with the
 remaining ships planned to be competitively awarded by the VCM.

 With the authorities granted in Section 128 of the FY 2025 National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA), the LSM program procured an existing design to construct a Non-Developmental Vessel (NDV). Top Level
 Requirements were approved in January 2025, enabling the selection of Damen Naval Landing Ship Transport (LST) 100 design in December 2025. Licensing an existing design has streamlined the design
 schedule with a complete contract design package ready to provide the winning VCM.

 This acquisition strategy is a key component of the Navy and Marine Corps' effort to address readiness in the Indo-Pacific and reflects a change in how the Navy traditionally contracts and oversees ship
 construction. Leveraging this new approach, the VCM will hold the prime contract with the Navy and, in turn, issue and manage its own commercial subcontracts directly with the shipyards. This places the VCM
 in direct contractual control of shipyard performance and creates a buffer that, along with a proven and unchanging design, is expected to reduce cost and schedule risks.

 The Commandant of the Marine Corps requirement for 35 Medium Landing Ships remains its primary modernization effort for distributed littoral operations, with a near-term Littoral Maneuver Bridging Solution
 needed until the LSM fleet is fielded. Littoral mobility is essential for the maneuver and sustainment of forces on critical littoral terrain within archipelagic environments, enhancing expeditionary agility and
 lethality. To address the recognized littoral mobility gap in the Indo-Pacific, the Marine Corps and Navy are developing the Medium Landing Ship. The LSM is designed to improve beach access, sustainment, and
 maneuverability in contested littoral environments, supporting the persistence of Naval Expeditionary Forces across the region.

 The FY 2027 request for LSM includes $0 thousand and quantity of 0 of discretionary and $1,887,500 thousand and quantity of 6 of mandatory for a total of $1,887,500 thousand and a quantity of 6. $1,698,000
 thousand of the mandatory funds will procure 6 LSMs. $189,500 thousand of the mandatory funds will be used to enhance the U.S surface maritime industrial base productivity in various areas including supplier$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                          Date: April 2026
