INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L010$$, 2026, $$POLLUTION CONTROL SYSTEMS/EQUIPMENT (PCE) PROGRAM
 Funds for the PCE Program are used to procure, install, and modernize Navy shipboard waste management equipment, systems, and technologies. The PCE Program ensures that Navy ships comply with
 applicable legal and statutory requirements (i.e., Federal laws and statutes, international regulations, and Department of War (DoW) and Navy instructions) governing environmental protection and shipboard
 discharge requirements. These requirements collectively restrict overboard discharge of oily wastewater, sewage, solid waste, plastic waste, and hazardous waste. Failure to comply risks potential personal, civil,
 and criminal liability; and can significantly impose constraints on the operational capabilities of Navy ships. Funding specifically supports procurements and installations for the Oil Pollution Abatement (OPA)
 Improvements program, the Dry Waste Processing Suites (DWPS) Improvements program, and the Hazardous Material Stowage Modernization program.

 SHORE BASED POLLUTION EQUIPMENT - (Logistics)
 The shore-based funds provide for equipment required to clean up Navy oil spills in the near shore to open sea environment and in areas distant from fixed bases as required by the Federal Water Pollution
 Control Act - Public Law 92-500, 33CFR154-155. The law created a National Oil and Hazardous Substance Pollution Contingency Plan and designates the DoW as one of the primary agencies responsible for
 promotion of effective operation of the plan. The Supervisor of Salvage is assigned the responsibility to provide technical expertise, resources, and equipment for response to Navy-originated spills of oil and
 other hazardous material in remote areas, coastal waters and/or the open sea. Major items of procurement include the following:

 [P40A / HF067 VESSEL SKIMMER SYSTEMS]: These systems are self-propelled skimmers designed for near-shore and low sea-state open ocean environments and are used in conjunction with oil containment
 boom for mechanical recovery of oil on the water. They are designed to be rapidly transportable to the scene of an oil spill.

 [P40A / HF068 UNDERWATER OIL RECOVERY SYSTEM]: A rapidly deployable system that provides grinders, sampling tools, sensors, cutters, connections, pumps, hoses, and hydraulic tools to locate,
 sample, penetrate, and offload tanks below the water.

 [P40A / HF069 42" BOOM REPLACEMENT SECTIONS]: Ocean Booming Systems (2000FT each) and Marco self-propelled skimming systems (600FT each) use standardized high buoyancy, high flexibility
 NAVY 42HB inflatable boom purchased in 55FT sections to provide phased replacement of rubber boom damaged or worn beyond economical repair. The other components of these systems have a longer
 useful life and need replacement at much longer intervals.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
